<h2>Floating UI Adapter</h2>
<p>
    The Floating UI Adapter bridges the <a href="https://floating-ui.com/">Floating UI</a> library to
    Web Everything as a <a href="/plugs/custompositioner/">positioning provider</a>, fulfilling the
    <a href="/intents/">Anchor Intent</a>. Register it once and any component delegating to
    <a href="/plugs/custompositioningregistry/"><code>CustomPositioningRegistry</code></a> uses Floating UI
    for placement, collision, and tracking — including the advanced middleware (autoPlacement, size, inline)
    beyond what the native-first default provides.
</p>

<section class="section-card fui-card">
    <h3 id="status">Status</h3>
    <p class="text-sm text-gray-600">
        <strong>Concept Phase:</strong> This adapter is in early design.
    </p>
</section>

<section class="section-card fui-card">
    <h3 id="concept">Concept</h3>
    <p>
        Floating UI provides robust positioning for tooltips, popovers, dropdowns, and other floating
        elements. The adapter is a thin class implementing the one-method <code>CustomPositioner</code>
        contract, so it slots into the registry alongside the native default and any other provider:
    </p>

    {% highlight "typescript" %}
import { computePosition, autoUpdate, offset, flip, shift } from '@floating-ui/dom';

class FloatingUIAdapter implements CustomPositioner {
    position(anchor, anchored, options) {
        const middleware = [
            options.offset != null && offset(options.offset),
            options.collision?.includes('flip') && flip(),
            options.collision?.includes('shift') && shift(),
        ].filter(Boolean);

        const update = () =>
            computePosition(anchor, anchored, { placement: options.placement, middleware })
                .then(({ x, y }) => Object.assign(anchored.style, { left: `${x}px`, top: `${y}px` }));

        // tracking: 'follow' → autoUpdate returns its own cleanup
        return options.tracking === 'follow'
            ? autoUpdate(anchor, anchored, update)
            : (update(), () => {});
    }
}

// Register the adapter as the application's provider
customPositioning.define('floating-ui', new FloatingUIAdapter());
    {% endhighlight %}

    <p>
        Components never reference Floating UI directly — they resolve <code>customPositioning</code> and call
        <code>position()</code>. Swapping to the native <code>'css-anchor'</code> provider (or another library)
        is a one-line registration change with no component edits.
    </p>
</section>

